s one childq why did you start your own businessa i had a vision of wanting to buy companies with niche brands and niche categories a lot of people talk about it a lot of people want to do it and there are some who do itq whya because i saw nobody doing it i saw nobody taking kosher foods medically directed foods health foods to the next level when we acquired kineret the packaging was thcentury packaging when i went to them and said we have to do lowfat and betterforyou foods they said nobody would eat them advertisement continue reading the main story q the people at kineret didnt believe ita they didnt and they didnt believe in spending money on advertising packaging or anything like that my philosophy was that if i bought a lot of small companies and brought the lessons i learned in corporate america my strategic vision and the entrepreneurealship that i had growing up as a kid and being in a family business that i could take all these little businesses to the next level they had not shown up on the screen of the big guys yet the big guys were not there continue reading the main story advertisement continue reading the main story q they didnt have these productsa right there was no big multifood company in the kosher food business the natural food business the medically directed food business and so i felt i couldnt get stomped on because there was no one thereq and what was the vision you said you hada my vision was making foods that taste good that were healthier types of food  whether they were low in fat lower in saturated fat lower in sodium foods for diabetics foods for people who kept kosher foods that only had natural ingredientsq and now products must contain a label with a listing of ingredientsa thats what really set me apart in  the nutritional labeling laws came into effect and everything became standardized that went in my favor because now people knew the percentage of saturated fat and how much sodium there was in there someone could call a product healthy but what were the calories we tell people read our labels read our ingredients were proud of whats in it so i wanted to build brands and provide foods that were better for youq what else was importanta i didnt want to be a manufacturer or own brick and mortar and build plants and stuff like that i like to keep things simple in my life and if i could concentrate on building a brand and let someone else manufacture these products for me under my formulas and recipes  and i had strict quality assurance in place  that was my strategy all the money i ever saved i put into this businessq did you borrow as wella i mortgaged my apartment and my wife is still working i took a big risk because i walked away from a sixfigure job i had no income and put my life on hold i was married two or three years and didnt want to have children because i had no income and the more people told me i was crazy that it wouldnt work the harder i workedq why did people think you were crazy what you were doing is called food consolidation righta well nobody ever really did it in the betterforyou category  in healthier foods i was the first and i was trying to do it with not a lot of money newsletter sign up continue reading the main story please verify youre not a robot by clicking the box invalid email address please reenter you must select a newsletter to subscribe to sign up you agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for the new york timess products and services thank you for subscribing an error has occurred please try again later you are already subscribed to this email view all new york times newsletters see sample manage email preferences not you privacy policy opt out or contact us anytime q how did you go about ita in my first year i bought four little companies  kineret farm foods pizsoy and california slim and i tried to take all of these four and merge them together why so they would have enough cash flow to pay some of the bills and people said that most people have trouble doing one acquisition youll never be able to pull four off so throughout the year i cant tell you how many times a deal was almost dead or how many times a bank slammed the door in my face as i tried to find the financing to acquire the companies i had deals with every one of them to go ahead and acquire them and i gave them money out of my own pocket that i would have lost if i couldnt get the necessary financingq so how did you finally pull it offa i found a small underwriter on long island lew liberbaum who took me public and raised me  million we went public in november  and after i paid off my debts i had  left so i knew i had to do something bigger a week after i closed on my initial public offering pet a large conglomerate was selling the hain hollywood division a  million division i flew to st louis to negotiate this deal with a letter from one of my investment banker friends that said i could raise  million and i won the bid and then went out and raised  million so in april  i acquired hain hollywood advertisement continue reading the main story q how did you manage all of thisa i had no infrastructure and hain was a business in st louis with a product line i operated out of the back of the kineret warehouse in jerichoq when did you move to uniondalea in august  and in our first year of owning hain we paid back  million of our debt in november  we bought estee from a large german company by again going out and borrowing the moneyq and you bought the licensing rights to weight watchers gourmet foods in march  so where do you see your future growth  in acquisitions or through the purchase of more licensing rightsa the no  way we grow is through new products and new distribution estee is a food product line for the diabetic as you know drug stores sell a lot of food and the no  perscription sold in a drugstore today is insulin but estee is not in drugstores yet so we have a big opportunity with drugstores we also have a big opportunity to expand hains weight watchers and others acquisitions are a big part of our growth were looking at acquisitions all the time and want to grow more through acquisitions than strategic alliances weight watchers is a great product line for us but we dont own the brand we want to own our brands we want to be a property owner not a property managerq a big part of your growth will be with organic foodsa yes over  percent of our westbrae products are organic and  or  percent of hain products are organic so we see a big growth in organic products diabetic products weight management products and kosher productsq what did you learn from your days with big companiesa to be expedient in doing things we came out with  new products in one year with hain when i worked in the big companies it would take us seven years to come out with  new products so strategic marketing being a visionary and making things happen quickly all came from big company experienceq in the future i understand you are looking at breakfast foods and baby productsa our companys natural foods today control six of the top  categories we want to introduce a lot of prepared meals for kids and were working on some prepared breakfasttype products wed like to go into baby food if we could find the right strategic acquisition what we want to do is introduce babies to organic or healthy food first and you bring new users into baby foods every nine months what we want to do then is introduce them into hain kids products i have a  yearold daughter and we have animal crackers in which there are no artificial colors flavors or preservatives and there is not a lot of sugar in this and its great for kidsq do you want your products in health food stores or supermarketsa both the natural food stores are great stores supermarkets today are also putting natural foods or betterforyou sections within their store and we want to be located in that section of the store i do not want my cookies in with keebler or nabisco cookies i want them in the natural food or betterforyou aisle when you are in specialty foods people are brand loyal when you mention a frozen challah the first thing that comes to your mind is kineret continue reading the main story we’re interested in your feedback on this page tell us what you think whats next loading go to home page » site index the new york times irwin simon  the hain celestial group europe jump to navigation organic  natural products for a healthy way of life™ our company our products my career live healthy contact us irwin simon a word from irwin simon ceo of the hain celestial group from the beginning we have advocated bringing healthier products to market and making them available in all types of stores and communities we have often led the way with unpopular positions that later proved to be right distinguishing our products from those of others with our commitment to wholesome eating for example we have never had transfats artificial flavors or colors and dyes or highfructose corn syrup in our natural foods and beverages we are also committed to helping to fight record high levels of obesity – tone of the most critical health concerns of our time hain celestial also takes steps every year to reduce our environmental footprint while strengthening our communities as we drive profitable business growth to us that is the true measure of success irwin simon